

import React from "react";

import ProjectSection from "./ProjectSection";
import AppSignals from "../../logic/AppSignals";
import {getItemData} from "../PortfolioItem";
import { LocationHashes } from "../../logic/Constants";
import BackToTopBtn from "./BackToTopBtn";

const itemData = getItemData(LocationHashes.whatsappRedesigned);

export default function WhatsAppRedesigned() {

	

	return <div className="project-content">
		
		<div className="cover">	

			<img
				
				className="cover-img"
				src="whatsapp/project-cover.png"
				loading="lazy"
				alt="Project cover"
			/>

			<div className="headings">
				<h1>{itemData.title}</h1>
				<h3>{itemData.caption}</h3>
			</div>

		</div>
		

		<ProjectSection mode="0" title="The problem" text={
			<React.Fragment>The web version of WhatsApp hasn't been getting much love in terms of 
				design from its parent company (likely because Facebook prioritizes Messenger).<br/>
			From squared corners and unnecessary elements, to a dark theme that took years to 
			arrive, only to disappoint in its execution.<br/>
			There's a lot to like about the app; it just needs a slight nudge in the right direction.<br/>
			Let's do this.
			</React.Fragment>
		}/>

		<ProjectSection mode="0" title="The Solution" text={
			<React.Fragment>Every section of the app is going to be scrutinized and updated if necessary. <br/>
				Once adjustments have been made in Figma, a browser extension will be developed, 
				targeting the elements to alter their style with CSS overrides.<br/>
			The add-on will be published for Chrome and Firefox, for everyone to enjoy.
			</React.Fragment>
		}/>

		
<ProjectSection mode="1" title="Color palette" text={
			<React.Fragment>1. App background<br/>
			2. Message background<br/>
			3. Chats list, header and input area background<br/>
			4. Input text field<br/>
			5. Heard audio graphics<br/>
			6. Messages text, chats list labels and default text<br/>
			7. Unheard audio graphics<br/>
			8. Original banner<br/>
			9. Original notifications<br/>
			<br/>
			The current palette uses dark backgrounds with a hint of blue. Such colors are suitable
			 for apps that look too neutral from lack of colored content, but that's not the case 
			 in WhatsApp, where we see lots of avatars, icons and media.<br/>
			Also, the dark blue is applied unevenly, ignoring elements like the header and the 
			input bar backgrounds, resulting in a palette that looks inconsistent and slightly unpolished.<br/>
			A neutral set of dark greys will look minimal, modern and elegant when contrasted by the rich colors of the assets.		
			</React.Fragment>
		} imgUrl="whatsapp/color-palette.jpg"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="Corner cuts" text={
			<React.Fragment>A prominent, 20px radius has been applied to the app's main container, instantly making it look modern and sleek.		
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/corner-cuts.png"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="Hidden search bar" text={
			<React.Fragment>The persistent search-bar that's rarely used has found a new home.<br/>
			Instead of permanently residing on the first spot of the chats list, it will now show 
			up when the search icon is clicked, then hide when not in use.			
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/hiding-search-bar.png"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="The original top banner" text={
			<React.Fragment>The personality of the original theme is a bit lost in the now 
				completely dark background. The green banner was a great way to promote the 
				branding colors, and gave the app a distinct look from other chat clients.<br/>
			Its shade of green is already unsaturated, making it a good fit for dark mode. 
			Its surface area is relatively small as it's partially covered by the app container.<br/>
			If you take into account those last two considerations, it makes sense to bring it back 
			without modifications.<br/>
			There's a big opportunity to get creative here, by bringing the background to life 
			with green lines or crazy patterns, but the goal of this particular redesign is not 
			to reinvent; it's to tastefully fix details.<br/>
			A complete redesign is also overdue for this app, so radical ideas can be saved for that next project.		
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/original top banner.png"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="Less borders" text={
			<React.Fragment>	Borders are useful for when there's a clear need for separation of 
				content items. If a reasonable amount of spacing can do the trick, the latter is 
				a better choice. Now the chats list looks minimal and softer, easier on the eyes.		
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/goodbye borders.jpg"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="Notification fill color" text={
			<React.Fragment>	A new message! But that doesn't look exciting at all. What about the original green? Yeap, that does the trick.		
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/notification fill color.jpg"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="Blue ticks" text={
			<React.Fragment>On one hand, WhatsApp's brand color is green. On the other, the ticks 
				themselves have always been blue. The trouble is that the light-blue looks off in 
				this environment, and it doesn't match the brand colors.<br/>
			The original notification green comes to the rescue again, making the 'read' 
			double-check match the rest of the app and look as lively and exciting as it's always been.			
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/blue ticks.png"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="About time" text={
			<React.Fragment>Proposal only - The message time label has always been out of alignment from the
				 message content, and its distance from the bottom is not even consistent with 
				 the padding it has to the right border.<br/>
			The way the app is coded makes it impractical to implement this fix, as the time 
			element needs to be removed from its parent and added at the same level as the 
			message label, instead of just changing the style. That would require to use JavaScript
			 to alter every message displayed and monitor new messages. Something infeasible for 
			 an extension that aims to alter the style as passively as possible.		
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/about time.png"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="Voice messages" text={
			<React.Fragment>Proposal only - The current style is quite outdated, and my suggested 
				fix would use a minimal waveform pattern. An implementation is not possible, as 
				the voice clips need to be analyzed in order to draw those cool waveforms. <br/>
				If a voice clip is automatically analized as soon as it arrives, the sender 
				will be informed that the receiver has played the audio.<br/>
			Mockups could be used instead, but they wouldn't represent the real message and would
			 therefore be misleading.		
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/voice messages.png"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="Message shape" text={
			<React.Fragment>Rounded borders are smooth, trendy and friendly. Also, those message
				 tails remove symmetry and provide no relevant information.<br/>
			The radius for the media containers has been updated accordingly.		
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/message shape.png"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="Message background" text={
			<React.Fragment>WhatsApp used a dark green for the background fill. Its saturation
				 is low to be in accordance with dark theme legibility practices, but it now 
				 looks dull. We'll fix this by using a dark grey, as neutral is better than dull. <br/>
				 Also, the notification green looks much more prominent this way.		
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/message background.png"/>

		<ProjectSection mode="1" title="Final result" text={
			<React.Fragment>Based on this stunning redesign, a browser extension was developed, now
				available on the <a 
				href = "https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/whatsapp-redesigned/mpdddinkocahocepimaeokdcfhgfibkk" 
				target = "_blank" rel = "noopener noreferrer">Chrome Store</a>, and already has over 250 happy users.
				<br/>
				
				The reception on <a 
				href = "https://www.reddit.com/r/whatsapp/comments/i9oqjx/i_redesigned_whatsapp_web_as_the_original_dark/" 
				target = "_blank" rel = "noopener noreferrer">reddit</a> was 99% positive.
			</React.Fragment>
		}
		imgUrl="whatsapp/WhatsApp Dark Mode.png"/>



		

		<h1 className="up-next">Up next</h1>

		
		<div className="about-me-card" onClick={() => AppSignals.aboutCardClicked.dispatch()}>
			<p>Ivan Cass</p>
		</div>
		

		<BackToTopBtn/>

</div>
}